    <h2>1. Soft Serve Machine Types & Detailed Pricing</h2>

    <p>The soft serve machine — often called a <strong>softy machine</strong> in India — is the most common piece of ice cream equipment you'll encounter. From highway dhabas to high-end QSR outlets, the softy machine produces that characteristic swirl of creamy, airy frozen dessert dispensed directly into a cone or cup. Understanding the different types is essential before comparing <strong>soft serve machine prices</strong>.</p>

    <h3>How a Soft Serve Machine Works</h3>
    <p>A soft serve machine takes a liquid ice cream mix (pre-made or made in-house), pumps it into a freezing cylinder, and simultaneously churns and freezes it. The mix enters at around 4°C and exits at about -6°C to -8°C. The churning action incorporates air (called "overrun") — typically 30% to 60% — which gives soft serve its light, creamy texture. The machine then holds the product at serving temperature until dispensed through a nozzle.</p>

    <p>Two key distinctions in soft serve machines:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Gravity-feed</strong>: Mix is poured into a top hopper and flows down by gravity into the freezing cylinder. Simpler, cheaper, and produces less overrun (denser product). Ideal for low-volume operations.</li>
      <li><strong>Air-pump (pressurised)</strong>: An air pump injects air into the mix as it enters the freezing cylinder. This gives more consistent overrun, lighter texture, and higher output per litre of mix (more servings per litre). Most commercial machines use this system.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Single-Nozzle Soft Serve Machine</h3>
    <p>A single-nozzle machine has one freezing cylinder and one dispensing nozzle. It produces one flavour at a time. This is the entry-level option for small businesses.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Entry-level Chinese-made (gravity, 8–10 L/hr)</strong>: ₹45,000 – ₹65,000</li>
      <li><strong>Mid-range (gravity, improved compressor, 10–12 L/hr)</strong>: ₹65,000 – ₹85,000</li>
      <li><strong>Air-pump single nozzle (12–15 L/hr)</strong>: ₹85,000 – ₹1,10,000</li>
      <li><strong>Countertop branded (Oceanpower, Spaceman)</strong>: ₹90,000 – ₹1,20,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Best for</strong>: Food stalls at events, small kiosks inside malls, tea/coffee shops adding a softy option, street vendors near schools and colleges.</p>

    <h3>Double-Nozzle Soft Serve Machine</h3>
    <p>A double-nozzle machine has two independent freezing cylinders, each with its own nozzle. You can serve two different flavours simultaneously. This is the most popular configuration for Indian ice cream parlours.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Economy double-nozzle (gravity, 18–20 L/hr)</strong>: ₹85,000 – ₹1,20,000</li>
      <li><strong>Mid-range (air pump, 20–25 L/hr)</strong>: ₹1,20,000 – ₹1,60,000</li>
      <li><strong>Premium branded (Oceanpower, 25 L/hr)</strong>: ₹1,60,000 – ₹2,00,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Best for</strong>: Dedicated softy counters, medium-traffic ice cream parlours, fast food outlets, and canteen or cafeteria operations.</p>

    <h3>Triple-Nozzle Soft Serve Machine (Twist)</h3>
    <p>The triple-nozzle machine is the flagship of soft serve. It has two freezing cylinders but three nozzles: one for each flavour and a centre nozzle that dispenses both flavours simultaneously, creating the iconic "twist" or "combo" swirl. This configuration maximises menu variety without additional cylinders.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Standard triple-nozzle (air pump, 25–30 L/hr)</strong>: ₹1,50,000 – ₹2,20,000</li>
      <li><strong>High-output floor model (30–40 L/hr, pre-cooling)</strong>: ₹2,20,000 – ₹3,00,000</li>
      <li><strong>Premium (Taylor, Carpigiani class, 35–50 L/hr)</strong>: ₹3,00,000 – ₹4,00,000</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Best for</strong>: High-traffic ice cream parlours, chains like McDonald's and Burger King (they use Taylor machines), event caterers, and franchised softy brands.</p>

    <h3>Countertop vs Floor-Standing Soft Serve Machines</h3>
    <p>Another important distinction is physical form factor:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Countertop</strong>: Compact, sits on an existing counter, suitable for low-to-medium volume. Typical hopper capacity: 3–8 litres per cylinder. Weighs 50–90 kg. Prices are 15–25% lower than equivalent floor models.</li>
      <li><strong>Floor-standing</strong>: Built on its own stand or wheeled base, larger hoppers (8–18 litres per cylinder), more powerful compressors, and often includes pre-cooling tanks. Essential for high-volume operations. Weighs 120–250 kg.</li>
    </ul>

