    <h3>Key Specifications to Compare</h3>
    <p>When comparing soft serve machines across brands, focus on these specifications:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Output per hour (L/hr)</strong>: This is the most important spec. A 15 L/hr machine can serve roughly 100–120 cones per hour (assuming ~120 ml per serve). Calculate your peak-hour demand first.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor type and power</strong>: Look for well-known compressor brands — Tecumseh, Copeland (Emerson), Embraco, or Panasonic. Compressor failure is the most expensive repair. Tropical-rated compressors are a must for Indian summers.</li>
      <li><strong>Hopper capacity</strong>: Larger hoppers mean less frequent refilling. A 7-litre hopper lasts roughly 45–60 servings before a refill.</li>
      <li><strong>Air pump vs gravity feed</strong>: Air pump machines give 30–50% more servings per litre of mix (higher overrun). Over a year, the mix savings alone can justify the higher machine cost.</li>
      <li><strong>Pre-cooling system</strong>: Premium machines have a pre-cooling tank that chills the mix before it enters the freezing cylinder. This improves consistency and extends mix shelf life in the hopper.</li>
      <li><strong>Night mode / standby</strong>: The machine maintains a higher temperature overnight to keep the mix safe but uses less power. Essential for businesses that operate daily.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>3. Batch Freezers for Hard Ice Cream</h2>

    <p>While a soft serve machine dispenses product directly to the customer, a <strong>batch freezer</strong> is used to make hard ice cream, gelato, sorbet, and other frozen desserts in batches. The product is then transferred to a blast freezer or hardening cabinet and stored in display freezers for scooping.</p>

    <h3>How a Batch Freezer Works</h3>
    <p>A batch freezer is essentially a powerful churning freezer. You pour your ice cream base (pre-aged for 4–24 hours) into the machine's cylinder. The cylinder wall is cooled to approximately -25°C to -35°C by a refrigeration system. A dasher (scraper blade) inside the cylinder continuously scrapes the frozen layer off the wall and mixes it into the base, incorporating air and creating a smooth, uniform texture. A typical batch takes 8–15 minutes depending on the recipe and machine capacity.</p>

