    <h2>6. Kulfi Making Machine: Equipment for India's Traditional Frozen Dessert</h2>

    <p>Kulfi — India's original frozen dessert — doesn't require the same machinery as ice cream. Traditional kulfi is set (not churned), which gives it its dense, creamy texture. However, commercial <strong>kulfi making machine</strong> equipment has evolved significantly for scale production.</p>

    <h3>Types of Kulfi Equipment</h3>

    <h4>Kulfi Mould Sets</h4>
    <p>The most basic kulfi "machine" is simply a set of moulds. For small-scale commercial production, stainless steel or aluminium kulfi moulds are dipped into a brine solution (salt + ice) in a matka or steel tub for setting.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Aluminium mould set (50 pieces, standard cone)</strong>: ₹5,000 – ₹10,000</li>
      <li><strong>Stainless steel mould set (50 pieces)</strong>: ₹10,000 – ₹18,000</li>
      <li><strong>Matka kulfi moulds (50 pieces)</strong>: ₹8,000 – ₹15,000</li>
      <li><strong>Stick kulfi moulds (100 pieces, popsicle-style)</strong>: ₹12,000 – ₹22,000</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Kulfi Setting Machines (Brine Tank)</h4>
    <p>For commercial kulfi production, a brine tank with a motorised stirrer provides consistent and faster setting. The moulds are submerged in chilled brine (-15°C to -20°C) that circulates around them.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Small brine tank (50–100 kulfi capacity)</strong>: ₹25,000 – ₹40,000</li>
      <li><strong>Medium brine tank (100–300 kulfi capacity)</strong>: ₹40,000 – ₹65,000</li>
      <li><strong>Large brine tank (300–500 kulfi capacity, motorised)</strong>: ₹60,000 – ₹80,000</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Kulfi Blast Freezer (Modern Method)</h4>
    <p>Modern commercial kulfi producers are increasingly using blast freezers instead of brine tanks. The kulfi mix is poured into moulds, placed on trays, and blast-frozen at -35°C to -40°C. This is faster, more hygienic, and produces more consistent results.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Small blast freezer (20–50 kg capacity)</strong>: ₹80,000 – ₹1,50,000</li>
      <li><strong>Medium blast freezer (50–100 kg)</strong>: ₹1,50,000 – ₹2,50,000</li>
    </ul>

    <p>For commercial kulfi production at scale, you'll also need a milk cooking and mixing vessel (khoya/mawa making), a <a href="/blog/sweet-making-machine-india">sweet making machine</a> setup, and cold storage. Many kulfi entrepreneurs start small with just moulds and a brine tank, then upgrade to blast freezers as volume grows.</p>

