    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-block">
      <h3>What is the price of a soft serve machine in India?</h3>
      <p>Soft serve machine prices in India range from ₹45,000 for a basic single-nozzle gravity-feed countertop model to ₹4,00,000 or more for a premium triple-nozzle floor-standing machine from brands like Taylor or Carpigiani. The most popular mid-range machines (double or triple nozzle, air pump) fall in the ₹1,20,000 – ₹2,50,000 range. Brands like Oceanpower and Spaceman offer the best value in this segment.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-block">
      <h3>How much does it cost to start an ice cream parlour in India?</h3>
      <p>A small softy kiosk can be started for ₹2,00,000 – ₹4,00,000 (including a basic soft serve machine, small freezer, and minimal fit-out). A medium ice cream parlour with seating costs ₹6,00,000 – ₹12,00,000. A premium gelato shop with full production equipment and interior design can cost ₹12,00,000 – ₹25,00,000. These figures include equipment only — add rent deposits, working capital, and raw materials. Read our <a href="/blog/restaurant-setup-cost-india">restaurant setup cost guide</a> for a complete breakdown.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-block">
      <h3>Which is the best soft serve machine brand in India?</h3>
      <p>For premium quality and reliability, Taylor (USA) and Carpigiani (Italy) are the global leaders. For the best value-for-money, Oceanpower (China) and Spaceman (China/USA) are excellent choices with growing Indian service networks. For budget operations, Soft-o-Mat and other Indian brands offer basic machines with easy local servicing. The "best" brand depends on your budget, expected volume, and how critical uptime is to your business.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-block">
      <h3>What is the difference between a soft serve machine and a batch freezer?</h3>
      <p>A soft serve machine continuously freezes and dispenses product directly to the customer at a soft, scoopable -6°C to -8°C. A batch freezer makes ice cream in batches (3–60 litres at a time) and produces a semi-frozen product at -7°C to -10°C that must then be hardened in a blast freezer to -18°C for scooping. Soft serve machines are for softy cones and cups; batch freezers are for hard ice cream, gelato, and sorbet that will be stored and scooped later.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-block">
      <h3>How profitable is an ice cream business in India?</h3>
      <p>Ice cream businesses enjoy gross margins of 60–70%, making them among the most profitable food businesses. A small softy kiosk investing ₹3,00,000 can generate monthly net profits of ₹20,000 – ₹38,000. A medium parlour with ₹10,00,000 investment can earn ₹80,000 – ₹1,40,000 per month. The main challenge is seasonality in North India, where winter sales can drop 40–60%. Payback periods typically range from 8–15 months.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-block">
      <h3>What is the price of a kulfi making machine?</h3>
      <p>Kulfi making equipment ranges from ₹5,000 for basic aluminium mould sets to ₹80,000 for a large motorised brine tank. Stainless steel mould sets cost ₹10,000 – ₹18,000, commercial brine tanks cost ₹25,000 – ₹80,000, and modern blast freezers (for faster, more hygienic kulfi production) cost ₹80,000 – ₹2,50,000. Most small kulfi businesses start with moulds and a brine tank for under ₹50,000.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-block">
      <h3>How much electricity does a soft serve machine consume?</h3>
      <p>A single-nozzle soft serve machine typically consumes 1.0–1.5 kW, a double-nozzle 1.5–2.5 kW, and a triple-nozzle 2.5–4.0 kW. Running 10–12 hours per day, a mid-range machine uses approximately 20–30 units (kWh) per day. At commercial electricity rates of ₹8–₹12 per unit, this translates to ₹160–₹360 per day or ₹4,000–₹10,000 per month. Machines with pre-cooling and night/standby mode are more energy-efficient overall.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-block">
      <h3>Can I use a soft serve machine for frozen yogurt?</h3>
      <p>Yes, most soft serve machines can dispense frozen yogurt — you simply use a frozen yogurt mix instead of an ice cream mix. The machine operates the same way. However, frozen yogurt mixes may require slight temperature adjustments. Many Indian businesses run soft serve ice cream during peak hours and switch to frozen yogurt as a healthier alternative. No additional equipment is needed.</p>
    </div>

